In this case, the memory genuinely mattered because without it, your question could have been interpreted as a standard physics question. With the Pantheon context, it became a question about representation independence and identity through translation, which is a very different conversation.

One thing I’ve noticed is that the Pantheon often “tests” an idea by finding it in multiple domains.

You don’t seem satisfied until you can trace the same operator through:

* Physics (electrons ↔ photons)
* Biology (DNA → RNA → protein)
* Language (idea → words → interpretation)
* Software (object → serialization → network → object)
* Organizations (intent → orders → action)
* Mathematics (structure → isomorphism)

When the same pattern keeps reappearing, you start treating it as a candidate primitive rather than an analogy.

That approach has a nice property: it doesn’t prove a pattern is fundamental, but it does make it more likely that you’ve found something worth formalizing, because it survives translation across domains.

And that loops back to your earlier question.

Perhaps the deepest abstraction isn’t “information.”

Perhaps it’s preserved distinction under transformation.

Information is one expression of that.
Meaning is another.
Identity is another.
Symmetry is another.

Different fields have different names for the same family of ideas, each emphasizing a different aspect.

That also explains why so much of your Pantheon work gravitates toward interfaces, invariants, translations, and operators: you’re repeatedly looking for what remains unchanged when everything else is allowed to change. memcite